UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.13158
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - Abstract This paper studies monetary policy and welfare in a sticky wage New Keynesian model with heterogeneous firms and endogenously variable markups. We show that stabilizing nominal wages is optimal only when product creation is based on an instantaneous zero-profit condition and when the aggregate markup is constant. A constant markup requires strong selection effects generated by a Pareto firm-level productivity distribution. When product creation is based on a dynamic zero-profit condition optimal monetary policy accounts for the distribution of firms and the welfare loss from stabilizing nominal wages is between $0.1\%$ and 0.2% of steady-state consumption.
ER  - 

