PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.13200
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - Abstract If productivity stems from the accumulation of ideas, then the ideas' production function can cause productivity and macro-economic aggregates to be persistent. We use this insight to estimate the parameters of the ideas' production function in a general equilibrium model. We find that ideas become harder to produce as they accumulate. We quantitatively explore the propagation of different kinds of shocks through the ideas' production function, finding that nonpersistent shocks that affect R&D decisions may lead to persistent productivity changes as a result. The use of capital in R&D is important for propagation.
ER  - 

